Comparison between sequences at 100% identity

References for taxonomical assignation: PR2 vs MareChiara

Lucia Campese

September 2020


Aim

The Aim is to compare distribution, biogeography and taxonomic composition of the metabarcoding V4 dataset taxonomically assigned to the genus Pseudonitzschia using two different reference databases:

  1. A revised version of the PR2 database (Guillouet al., 2013) for which the Chlorophyta sequences had been checked against the latest taxonomy (Traginet al., 2016) [info to be confirmed] => TARA-PR2 ;

  2. A selection of 27 Pseudonitzschia species sequences (from Valeria R.) from MareChiara V4 dataset => TARA-MC


Dataset

Data: TARA Oceans and Tara Oceans Polar circle metabarcording (V4)
Taxon: Pseudonitzschia
Geographic scale: Global

The two datasets are quite different in the number of amplicons. TARA-PR2 has 17 sequences, while TARA-MC has 324. There are 8 shared sequences between the two. In terms of species, they share 4 species, with TARA-PR2 containing 3 species never detected in TARA-MC, and the latter with 17 species never annotated in TARA-PR2.

The total number of reads (plot on the left) is higher than 400000 in both datasets, with TARA-MC containing around 50000 of reads more than TARA-MC.

By looking at the distribution of the total number of reads per each amplicon (plot on the right), we can notice that TARA-MC has a high number of sequences with few read counts, and few very abundant sequences. This is not evident for TARA-PR2, that displays a more eterogeneous pattern.


  1. How is the distribution of richness and abundance per sampling station?
rbind(final_tara_pr2, final_tara_mc) %>%
  mutate(Station.label = substr(Station.label, 6, 8)) %>% 
  group_by(Station.label, dataset) %>% 
  summarise(tot.reads.station = sum(readcounts),
         richness.station.spp =n_distinct(species)) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  pivot_longer(tot.reads.station:richness.station.spp) %>% 
  ggplot() +
  aes(x=Station.label, y=value, col=dataset, group=dataset) +
  geom_line(size=1.5) +
  theme_bw() +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("TARA-MC" = "lightgreen",
                               "TARA-PR2" = "skyblue")) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle=50, size=6, vjust = 0.5))  +
  facet_wrap(~ name, scales = "free", nrow = 2)

rbind(final_tara_pr2, final_tara_mc) %>%
  mutate(Station.label = substr(Station.label, 6, 8)) %>% 
  group_by(Station.label, dataset) %>% 
  summarise(tot.reads.station = sum(readcounts)) %>% 
  ungroup() %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_histogram(aes(tot.reads.station, fill = dataset), alpha=0.5) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  scale_x_log10() +
  xlab("abundance per station") +
   scale_fill_manual(values = c("TARA-MC" = "lightgreen",
                               "TARA-PR2" = "skyblue")) +
  ggtitle("Pseudo-nitzschia abundance expressed as number of reads per station") +
  facet_wrap(~dataset, scales="free_y")

The richness - i.e.number of species detected - (upper plot) follows the same trend between the two datasets along the sampling stations, with few exceptions (i.e.stations 31, 47, 54). This trend is even more evident when looking at the total abundance per station - expressed as total number of read counts per stations- (bottom plot), where the two lines overlap for almost all samples. One exception is the case of station 155, where TARA-MC exceeds TARA-PR2 by 4000 units ca.

  1. Is there a correlation between richness and abundance?
corpr2 <- rbind(final_tara_pr2, final_tara_mc) %>%
  mutate(Station.label = substr(Station.label, 6, 8)) %>% 
  group_by(Station.label, dataset) %>% 
  summarise(tot.reads.station = sum(readcounts),
            richness.station.spp =n_distinct(species)) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  filter(dataset == "TARA-PR2")

corpr2.res<-psych::corr.test(corpr2$richness.station.spp, corpr2$tot.reads.station, method = "spearman")
#print(corpr2.res, short = F)

print("correlation between richness and abundance in TARA-PR2")
## [1] "correlation between richness and abundance in TARA-PR2"
cor.test(corpr2$richness.station.spp, corpr2$tot.reads.station, method = "spearman")

  1. Is there spatial autocorrelation?
print("TARA-PR2")
## [1] "TARA-PR2"
final_tara_pr2 %>% 
  mutate(Station.label = substr(Station.label, 6, 8)) %>% 
  group_by(Station.label, dataset) %>% 
  summarise(sum = sum(readcounts)) %>% 
  ungroup() %>%
  arrange(Station.label) %>% 
  pull(sum) %>% 
  acf

print("TARA-MC")
## [1] "TARA-MC"
final_tara_mc %>% 
  mutate(Station.label = substr(Station.label, 6, 8)) %>% 
  group_by(Station.label, dataset) %>% 
  summarise(sum = sum(readcounts)) %>% 
  ungroup() %>%
  arrange(Station.label) %>% 
  pull(sum) %>% 
  acf

The plots show thata there is spatial autocorrelation in TARA-PR2.

In particular, in TARA-PR2 graph (left) there is one spike at 1 that clearly falls outside the bonds, meaning that the total abundance in each station consistently influences the abundance in the following station.

Moreover, in both dataset there is a peak at 14 that slightly exceeds the outside bonds and one at 15 that almost does.

Besides that, the abundance per station values are independent of each other if only trying to explain them with themselves (the autocorrelation property).

How to deal with that? Spatial autocorrelation have implications when applying statistical methods (to be discussed)

library(scatterpie)

combined_datasets_mappie <- rbind(final_tara_pr2, final_tara_mc) %>% 
  group_by(Station.label, dataset) %>% 
  mutate(tot.abundance.per.station = sum(readcounts),
         Lat = mean(Latitude),
         Long = mean(Longitude)) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  group_by(species, dataset) %>% 
  mutate(occupancy = n_distinct(Station.label)) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  mutate(species_sel = ifelse(occupancy < 50, "others (*)",
                              as.character(species))) %>% 
  group_by(species_sel, Station.label, dataset) %>% 
  mutate(sel.species.abundance.per.station = sum(readcounts),
         fraction = sel.species.abundance.per.station/tot.abundance.per.station) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  select(Station.label, Long, Lat, species_sel, fraction, dataset) %>% 
  arrange(Station.label) %>% 
  unique()  %>% 
  group_by(Station.label) %>% 
  mutate(radius = max(fraction)*4) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  spread(species_sel, fraction) %>% 
  mutate_all(funs(ifelse(is.na(.), 0, .)))


base_world3 + 
  geom_scatterpie(aes(x=Long, y=Lat, r=radius),
                  data=combined_datasets_mappie,

  1. What about size classes? Which one holds the highest number of sequences? Is there overlap among different classes?
print("Combining the two dataset; Overlap considering seqId")
## [1] "Combining the two dataset; Overlap considering seqId"
rbind(final_tara_pr2, final_tara_mc) %>% 
  unite("Fraction.size", lower.size.fraction:upper.size.fraction, sep = "-") %>% 
  mutate(Fraction.size = case_when(Fraction.size %in% c("3-20", "5-20") ~ "nano",
                                 Fraction.size == "20-180" ~ "micro",
                                 Fraction.size == "180-2000" ~ "meso",
                                 TRUE ~ "other")) %>%
  select(seqId, readcounts, Fraction.size) %>%
  group_by(seqId, Fraction.size) %>%
  summarise(sum = sum(readcounts)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(sum = ifelse(sum > 0,  1, 0)) %>%
  spread(Fraction.size, sum) %>%
  mutate_at(vars(-seqId), funs(ifelse(is.na(.), 0, .))) %>%
  select(-c("seqId", "other")) %>%
  venn::venn(ellipse = F, borders = F,  cexil = 0.8, cexsn = 0.9)
